After checking the HubConfigImpl, I think we can simplify unnecessary calls here. We even do not need to check if the hubConfigImpl.getAppConfig() is null because it is null for sure.
HubConfigImpl.java
protected void hydrateAppConfigs(Properties properties) {
    com.marklogic.mgmt.util.PropertySource propertySource = properties::getProperty;

    if (appConfig != null) {
        // Still need to call this since the setter also "updates" appConfig with DHF-specific values
        setAppConfig(appConfig);
    } else {
        DefaultAppConfigFactory appConfigFactory = new DefaultAppConfigFactory(propertySource);
        if (hubProject != null && !StringUtils.isEmpty(hubProject.getProjectDirString())) {
            appConfigFactory.setProjectDir(hubProject.getProjectDir().toFile());
        }
        setAppConfig(appConfigFactory.newAppConfig());
    }

}
