Yes, I think the root cause is how we glue those HubConfig/HubProject/AppConfig together. For one-ui installation case, we only need to deal with the situation when AppConfig is null.  And my gut feeling is that passing a valid project directory to AppConfig is always what we expect.  Plus I think the one-ui higher level api call should be simplier during createProject/refreshProject. For me, the following calls are confused and a hacker way to workaround.
public void afterPropertiesSet() in HubConfigSession class

        if (hubConfigImpl.getAppConfig() == null) {
            hubConfigImpl.setAppConfig(new AppConfig(), true);
            hubConfigImpl.setAppConfig(new AppConfig(Paths.get(projectDirectory).toFile()), true);
        }
        hubConfigImpl.createProject(environmentService.getProjectDirectory());
        hubConfigImpl.createProject(projectDirectory);
        hubConfigImpl.refreshProject();
        // resetting app config to trigger updates to values
        hubConfigImpl.setAppConfig(hubConfigImpl.getAppConfig(), false);
        hubConfigImpl.hydrateConfigs();

